<HEADLINE>
<P>
PROFIT RIGHTS FOR PATIENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After reading the article about John Moore ("Case Argues Rights Over Tissue 
Used in Research," Part A, April 11) appealing to the state Supreme Court after 
his cancerous spleen was removed which saved his life, to grant medical 
patients the right to share in profits from the commercial use of their tissue, 
I decided that if he wins, he is setting a weird precedent. 
</P>
<P>
Picture this: When people have surgery, they tell their doctor that any organ 
removed from their body belongs to them and that they are to be kept informed 
as to what is done with it. 
</P>
<P>
So the scientific community discovers, as in Moore's case, that the diseased 
organ has valuable properties that would greatly aid humankind. What happens 
next? Do the doctors and medical research center implement their medical 
findings or do they first figure out the monetary value of the patient's organ? 
</P>
<P>
In the meanwhile, I have elected to donate my organs upon my death. Perhaps I 
should qualify this by stating that if they find anything of value to notify my 
heirs. 
</P>
<P>
JEANNE LONDE 
</P>
<P>
Northridge 
</P>
</TEXT>
