<HEADLINE>
<P>
ARMY REJECTS COMBAT ROLES FOR WOMEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Army said Thursday it has rejected a recommendation for a four-year test 
that would allow women to hold combat-related jobs. 
</P>
<P>
"The Army does not feel that a test is warranted. We feel our current policy 
reflects the intent of Congress by excluding women from the highest risk of 
direct combat," the service said in a statement released at the Pentagon. 
</P>
<P>
The recommendation was made last fall by the Defense Advisory Committee on 
Women in the Services. The panel was founded in 1951 and advises the Department 
of Defense on women's issues. 
</P>
<P>
"We currently offer women full career opportunities and maintain equitable 
advancement in schooling and promotion selection rates," the Army statement 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
