<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: OXNARD; 
</P>
<P>
18-YEAR-OLD SENTENCED IN SCHOOL FIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MACK REED 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An 18-year-old Oxnard student has been sentenced to seven years and eight 
months in the California Youth Authority for setting a fire that destroyed most 
of Hueneme High School's administration wing in October. 
</P>
<P>
However, the youth cannot be held past his 21st birthday because he was a minor 
when he set fire to his school, said Deputy Dist. Atty. 
</P>
<P>
Eric Bond. The Oct. 14 fire, which was set in Assistant Principal Daisy Tatum's 
office, caused an estimated $400,000 to $800,000 of damage, Bond said. 
</P>
<P>
Bond said the Ventura County district attorney's office will seek some form of 
probation for the youth after he turns 21. He declined to name the youth 
because of his age at the time of the fire. 
</P>
<P>
Investigators never determined the motive for the fire, and said there is no 
evidence that it was aimed at Tatum. "It was an angry attack on a fundamental 
institution of this society, on the schools," Bond said. 
</P>
<P>
A 14-year-old who acted as lookout during the arson and a 16-year-old who 
kicked in a school window to let the arsonist inside were found guilty of 
burglary, but were never charged with arson, Bond said. They have since been 
expelled from Hueneme High School. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hueneme High School officials and counselors are working in four 
trailers, which were set up on school grounds as temporary offices after the 
fire, Tatum said. MACK REED 
</P>
</TEXT>
