<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
JAPAN'S STEEL EXPORTS TAKE DIVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Japan's steel exports in fiscal 1989 hit a 19-year low largely because of 
sluggish sales to its major customers, China and the Soviet Union, the Iron and 
Steel Federation said in a preliminary report today. 
</P>
<P>
The federation said exports in the fiscal year, which ended March 31, were 
estimated at 18.99 million metric tons, down 18.3% from the preceding year and 
the lowest since fiscal 1970, when Japan's overseas sales totaled 19.75 million 
tons. 
</P>
<P>
Federation officials said there is little possibility that Japan's sluggish 
steel exports will pick up although domestic demand will remain strong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA042090-0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 207281 </DOCID>
