<P>
AVON'S JAPAN DEAL FALLS THROUGH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Avon Products Inc. said today that a $450-million deal has fallen through in 
which the cosmetics giant was to sell its 60% interest in Avon Japan to Friends 
of Freesia Co. of Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
John Cox, a spokesman for Avon, said the company declined to extend the closing 
on the transaction, which was to have included a $338-million cash payment and 
two separate royalty prepayments of $70 million and $42 million, until June as 
had been requested by the buyer. 
</P>
<P>
Avon, which previously extended the closing date until April 27 from March 30, 
said it "still plans to sell all or part" of its interest in Avon Japan. Cox 
said the company hoped to complete a deal by year-end. "There are a number of 
potential buyers," Cox said. 
</P>
<P>
Avon said it will exercise its right to collect a $6.3-million escrow deposit 
from Friends of Freesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
